body:
@Data-drone, thanks for bringing this up!

I looked into it, and it relates to two issues of "unintuitiveness" around `DatetimeIndex` in version 0.7.0:

* if `predict` is given an absolute horizon, it breaks, instead of converting into a `ForecastingHorizon`. This was highlighted by @flix6x in #1167, and has been addressed in the newest development version. So the *first* breakage point is resolved, just not in the version that's on `pip`. It will be in the next release.
* the second error relates to the convention tha `DatetimeIndex` must have a `freq` parameter set - yours is likely `None`. The reason is that without this most methods can't easily translate the dates into integer multiples of a period, internally. If you created the index yourself, you may want to set it explicitly or infer it, see the [`pandas` docs here](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DatetimeIndex.html).

Looking at this second point, I agree that the message is ambiguous and the behaviour is unintuitive.

I would hence propose is the following behaviour in this case, i.e., if the index is `DatetimeIndex` and `freq` is `None` (not set), in `predict`:

* integer index is assumed on both train data and forecast horizon
* a warning message is displayed for forecasters that cannot handle non-equally spaced data, stating that the method is considering it equally spaced

@Data-drone, what do you think of this behaviour? @flix6x, what do you think (since this is closely related to your problem in #1167)?

@mloning, @aiwalter (authors of original `fh` logic), FYI, any comments?
